  "prompt": "How can I simplify [math]\\frac{1}{1+x^{m-n}}+ \\frac{1}{1+x^{n-m}}?[/math]",
  "response": "To simplify the expression:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{1 + x^{m - n}} + \\frac{1}{1 + x^{n - m}}\n\\]\n\nwe can follow these steps:\n\n1. **Express the Exponents Consistently:**\n   \n   Notice that:\n   \\[\n   x^{n - m} = \\frac{1}{x^{m - n}}\n   \\]\n   \n   Let \\( y = x^{m - n} \\). Then:\n   \\[\n   x^{n - m} = \\frac{1}{y}\n   \\]\n   \n2. **Rewrite the Expression:**\n   \n   Substitute \\( y \\) into the original expression:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{1}{1 + y} + \\frac{1}{1 + \\frac{1}{y}}\n   \\]\n   \n3. **Simplify the Second Fraction:**\n   \n   \\[\n   \\frac{1}{1 + \\frac{1}{y}} = \\frac{y}{y + 1}\n   \\]\n   \n   Therefore, the expression becomes:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{1}{1 + y} + \\frac{y}{y + 1}\n   \\]\n   \n4. **Combine the Fractions:**\n   \n   Since both fractions have the same denominator:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{1 + y}{1 + y} = 1\n   \\]\n   \n5. **Final Simplification:**\n   \n   The entire expression simplifies to:\n   \\[\n   1\n   \\]\n   \n**Final Answer:**\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{1}\n\\]",
  "temperature": 1.0,
